# Chapter 6 — Records + types

Records give you a named tuple with predicate + accessors. Motoi Scheme adds `type-of` and `describe` so you can inspect anything.

## `define-record`

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(define-record point (x y))
(define p (point 3 4))
(point-x p)
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(point? p)
</pre>

## `type-of`

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(type-of 42)
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(type-of \"hello\")
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(type-of (list 1 2 3))
</pre>

## `describe`

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(describe 'map)
</pre>

> **Sakura says**
>
> When I don't know what I'm looking at, `describe` is my first move. Second move: `,help <verb>` in the REPL — it prints the docstring plus a novice / intermediate / expert example.

